column1: As of 8 November 2022, how many birds in commercial and backyard flocks will have confirmations of highly pathogenic avian flu (HPAI) in 2022, according to the USDA?
column4: More than 50 million but fewer than 70 million

Well, this question sure got me! I don't understand why we haven't seen more big farms being hit this fall. Maybe the birds just aren't in the states with big poultry operations yet? Anyway, great question, and for the sake of the birds and the farmers, I'm glad this question resolved substantially lower than I thought it would.
The total stands at 49.00M as of Nov 3, with a big 1.1M farm hit in Iowa. I think the odds that another ~1M farm will be hit in the next 5 days of data are small.
Thought really hard about not bothering to update this close to the end, but there is a nonzero chance another large farm tests positive in the next 4 days.
I don't understand how more big commercial farms aren't being hit, but it's a great thing that they're not! Bin 2 is looking most likely now.
Well, very surprisingly, the chance that we're going to see >2.24M birds affected in the next 11 days seems somewhat small at this point.
I still don't get why so few commercial farms and birds have been affected in October vs. September, but it's great that they haven't been!

the data resets/limits to 4 months on that website, and not sure how to enlarge it , somehow it keep limiting, so no clue what is the total count for this year so far. Based on earlier updates from @belikewater understand need 2.7M to add in Oct and first days of November. Today means another 2.0M to come in next 15 days. I am increasing the chance it doesn't happen though a big shot entry just blows it apart.

I am extremely surprised by how October is going. Granted, there is a large stochastic element, and the total number of birds affected depends largely on large farms getting hit, but I would have expected at least 1 or 2 farms with >1M birds to be affected in October by now. But while more *backyard* flocks have been affected in October so far than in September, fewer *commercial* farms have been affected so far. I have no idea whether this reflects enhanced biosecurity among egg and poultry producers, sheer luck, or a combination of both, but the result is <1M birds affected so far in October, when 6.15M were affected in September. So, I am raising my forecast a bit further on bin 2. There is only 2.27M to go to reach 50M, and I still think that's highly likely to be reached, but it might not be. The top 10 poultry-inventory states have almost completely been bypassed lately. It's weird, and I don't understand it.
I find it baffling that October has so far seen about 0.7M poultry affected, when September saw 6.15M.
https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-nears-record-poultry-deaths-bird-flu-virus-type-complicates-fight-2022-10-18/
Repeating my forecast. The total is at 47.17M. 6.15M affected birds in Sept. Oct will likely end up roughly comparable. 2.83M to go to reach 50M.
It's already Oct 4, and we haven't hit 50M yet, so bin 4 looks almost impossible at this point. I'm really at about 0.5% for bin 4.

September ended at 46.75M, i.e., with ~6.75M added so far in the fall migration season. With 5.5 more weeks to go in the forecast period, at this point, I think it would be extraordinary for the total to end up over 70M. Detections just aren't ramping up. It looks like this season will be fairly similar to the spring season.

I don't see evidence of any speed-up in birds affected, so I'm increasing my forecast on the 50-70M bin. I'm still leaving 15% on the higher bin because it's still possible that next month could see a string of large farms hit.
Big thanks to @belikewater for brilliant insight on this question

Highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI) strains have become endemic this year in North American waterfowl. ("Highly pathogenic" here refers only to the ability of these strains to cause disease in domestic poultry.) Bird flu spreads to domestic poultry primarily during the spring and fall migrations of waterfowl. HPAI strains became endemic in Europe before they did in N America, so Europe has seen bird flu spreading to domestic poultry with both the spring and fall migrations. Before now, the US has only seen major outbreaks that last one migration season. But, this is now changing because HPAI is now endemic in N America, too; for the first time, we now have major HPAI outbreaks in 2 consecutive migration seasons.
Bin 2 is impossible. There's no way there won't be at least 4M more birds affected.
Less than 3.6M to go to reach 50M, as the fall migration ramps up.

Reducing bins 2 and 4 a tiny bit. We're in late September and already >45M, so I don't see how it's plausible that the next 6 weeks will add <5M, as the migration season ramps up. Similarly, we're in late September and only at just over 45M, so it seems increasingly unlikely that we could add >25M in the next 6 weeks, although I don't think it would be impossible, particularly if states with large operations were to get hit.
The crowd forecast on bin 2 is starting to come down now.

Lowering my forecast on bin 2 almost to 0%. If we see a big farm hit about once every 2 weeks, with an average of ~2M birds affected, and a steadily growing stream of smaller farms being hit, then with today's total at 43.93M, I just don't see how the total could stay under 50M in the next 8 weeks. I'll expect the total to be around 46M by the end of Sept, and firmly in bin 3 on Nov 8. I'm still leaving open the possibility of a higher total, in case detections heat up faster than in spring.

I really don't think bin 2 is possible, but I'll leave a little weight on it just in case. I also think bin 4 would require a substantial number of very large farms to be hit, and I don't think the required rate is likely, based on what we're seeing so far this fall and on what we saw last spring. Also, I think producers are already circling the wagons to prepare for bird flu's return, as a variety of news sources are warning commercial and backyard poultry producers to expect more HPAI this fall. The more bird flu is around, the more producers will step up biosecurity. (Kind of the opposite of the situation with Covid.) Still, a lot is up to chance.
Realistically, bin 4 is less likely. Adjusting down.

There's a lot of randomness in how many birds are affected each week or month, but given that we're already at 43.8M on Sept 6, I think the 50M threshold is likely to be crossed sometime this month. Still, the current total just jumped 3M because of one commercial layer operation in Ohio, and that size of hit is rare. So I'll leave a little weight on bin 2, but I'll also increase my forecast on bin 4 in case things continue to heat up. At 4M/week, the total would end up >70M. And the season is just starting.
I found a couple interesting articles:

Tweaking my forecast a little. I think bin 4 isn't likely if the fall is similar to the spring, but it should be kept in mind that the fall could be worse than the spring. More than 50M birds were lost in the spring 2015 outbreak; there is variability across seasons and years. Nonetheless, because the question ends in early November, I think bin 4 is fairly unlikely. I'll also increase my forecast on bin 2 in case this fall is milder, as there haven't been large losses yet.
Shifting my forecast a little to favor bin 3 +5% and bin 4 -5%, after thinking about the situation some more.

Adjusting my forecast a bit upwards. HPAI H5N1 is still being detected at low levels in the US. And it's in Canada. It's in wild waterfowl populations up north for the summer. The USDA said months ago that it's becoming dominant in wild waterfowl populations in North America. I expect that we'll start seeing more of it with the fall migration, which will start in a few weeks. I don't really see a good reason why it would affect substantially fewer birds in fall than in spring; poultry producers were already prepared for it in spring. But maybe producers will be even more careful after last spring. But, viruses do mysterious things, so I also don't rule out the possibility that HPAI mostly goes away and is replaced by some other low path strains; that's bin 2.https://www.usgs.gov/centers/nwhc/science/distribution-highly-pathogenic-avian-influenza-north-america-20212022
I guess I'll give it 50/50 that there will be a fall outbreak.
Bin 1 is out. I expect a small number of birds affected to be added this month, and then spring migration cases to wrap up. Then I'll wait for the fall migration, which I think could see 0-50+M.
Well, that's it then for bin 1...

A big commercial farm was surprisingly just hit in CO, and the total is now 39.87M. I expect spring cases to wrap up in the next week or 2. 130k more to reach 40M. There were ~103k birds affected from May 18 through today, and ~183k affected from May 17 through today. I think it's very likely the total by the end of this month and the end of the spring migration will be <40M. But obviously, if it is, it will be very close. Still, I think there's a real possibility that the total will remain under 40M by the end of the month and that there won't be a fall outbreak, so I'm leaving substantial weight on bin 1 for now. I really can't narrow the forecast down between any of the 4 lowest bins at this time. And 50.4M poultry were affected in 2014-15 outbreak, so I suppose I should leave open the possibility of another 50M+ in the fall. I don't understand why the crowd is so low on bin 4 at this time, though; if 40M are affected in the spring migration, it would seem possible that 40M could also be affected in the fall, if HPAI continues to circulate in N American waterfowl.

I don't understand why the crowd is so low on bin 1. The spring-migration outbreak is almost wrapped up, the total as of June 1 is 37.94M, and there may not even be a fall outbreak. I think we can expect <1M additional birds affected to be added by mid-June, and then that will be it until the fall. In 2015, there wasn't a fall outbreak. I think a fall outbreak is somewhat likely because HPAI H5N1 has become dominant in waterfowl in N America, but it's far from guaranteed. So, I think bin 1 is still very much a live option. I think that any fall outbreak would be at most in a similar range, so we could end up with a total anywhere in bins 1 through 4.

I don't understand why the crowd is at 1% on bin 1, unless it's just that people haven't looked at the question in a while. The spring migration is wrapping up, Iowa (with the largest chicken inventory in the country) hasn't had a confirmed case since May 4, and no flock with at least 100k birds has been affected since May 3. The total as of today is 37.95M, and it may well stay under 40M by the end of the spring migration. Then we have to worry about fall migration; there may or may not be any cases in the fall. I do think it's more likely than not that we'll see some, as HPAI has become dominant in N American waterfowl, but it's also possible we won't see any substantial numbers. We didn't see much in fall 2015. So, I'm giving bin 1 a big chance. I think any number between 38M and 80M is possible, so I have to assign a fairly low probability to 4 bins, which means I'll probably have a bad score lol.
halfway through may and it looks like commercial flocks are avoiding infection

Iowa hasn't been hit recently, and the only top 10 states in terms of chicken inventory that have had cases recently are Pennsylvania and Michigan. It's looking increasingly possible that we could sneak through the end of the spring migration without reaching 40M. Then the question would be whether there will be a fall outbreak with fall migration. Increasing bin 1 forecast just in case.
Outbreak seeems under control, 45 million at 8th November if current increase, less than 40 if not.
Birds affected during spring migration will probably end up over 40M, and fall could end up seeing 0 through the same.

I'm allowing some possibility of bin 1 now. The states with the most poultry are being less affected now, and big producers are likely taking careful precautions. It's possible that we won't see many or any more big flocks hit with the spring migration. And it's possible that HPAI won't return in the fall, although I think it will. There's a wide range of possibilities here. I'll probably end up with a terrible score by hedging against the full range.
It looks like earlier peak and heightened surveillance instead of a much worse outbreak. There are there are another six weeks until mid June, which was the last of the 2014-15 reports.

The total through April 30 is 36.66M. This pretty much rules out bin 1, as cases would have to fall off too rapidly to stay under 40M. It's not plausible that May through June would see less than 3.34M birds affected. So, I'm zeroing out bin 1.

I'm drastically reducing my forecast on bin 1. April 28's total is 35.52M, which is about where I thought we might be for all of April. Another big commercial operation was hit in Nebraska yesterday, affecting 2.1M birds. Also, it looks possible that spread is occurring between farms in Lancaster County, PA, as they are having a lot of outbreaks there on commercial farms in close succession, starting on April 15 and still ongoing. As my forecast was that the total would end up very close to 40M with most inter-farm spread being prevented, I think the big hit in Nebraska plus ongoing spread in Lancaster, PA will very likely tip the balance over 40M. PA is #4 in the country in the number of chickens in 2021, at ~37M, so there's a lot of possibility for damage. And PA wasn't hit hard in the 2015 outbreak, so their poultry farms may not have developed a culture of biosecurity at the level needed to prevent the spread of bird flu. I think we can expect to see more commercial operations affected in Lancaster, PA in the coming days and possibly weeks, and possibly in neighboring counties as well, if the outbreak spills over.

A few things jump out. Number of findings continues to increase. Wild bird findings (per USGS) have occurred in the south, but not so far in domestic fowl. I think domestic fowl findings are inevitable. Since Georgia is a major poultry state, I expect a lot of problems there. Not so sure about S. Carolina and Tennessee. This is a sad and depressing, but important question. I think the key to this question is understanding how bird flu is transmitted to poultry. The reservoir for this disease is waterfowl, and it's a gastrointestinal disease in waterfowl. It spreads to commercial and backyard flocks and other birds through the droppings of migrating birds; the virus gets into poultry areas directly, by droppings falling into poultry areas, or indirectly, by inadvertently being brought into poultry areas on clothing, shoes or equipment. The goal of USDA policy is to prevent infections caused by wild birds and local spread between farms through good biosecurity practices. Migratory waterfowl that are the primary carriers of this disease largely migrate to Canada, with resident populations also in the northern US, especially around the Great Lakes; if local spread can be eliminated, then once the spring migration season is over, infection risks will recede to close to zero. The threat may then return with the fall migration season.
It could be similar to the 2015 outbreak, but peaking a few weeks early or at least four times worse.
